senses.sense: (transitive) To eject abruptly; to throw out suddenly and swiftly.
(intransitive) To say abruptly.
(biology, transitive) To eject or suddenly throw fluid or some other substance from a duct or other body structure.
(specifically transitive and intransitive) Of a human being or other mammal: to forcibly eject from the urethra in response to sexual stimulation, in a male, semen; and, in a female, vaginal fluid.
examples: Men can ejaculate between 0.1 and 10 milliliters of semen on average. (transitive)
With a groan, he ejaculated on his abdomen. (intransitive)

senses.sense: (transitive, rare) To sexually stimulate (someone) so that they eject fluid from the urethra.
Fluid or some other substance ejected or suddenly thrown from a duct or other body structure; specifically, semen or vaginal fluid ejected by a human being or other mammal during an ejaculation.

The act of throwing or darting out with a sudden force and rapid flight.
The uttering of a short, sudden exclamation or prayer, or the exclamation or prayer uttered.
(biology) The act of ejecting or suddenly throwing, as a fluid from a duct or other body structure.
(specifically) A reflex in human beings and other mammals in response to sexual stimulation involving the forcible ejection from the urethra of, in males, semen; and, in females, vaginal fluid.

ejaculation; ejaculate
(transitive) To compel (a person or persons) to leave.
examples: The man started a fight and was ejected from the bar.
Andrew was ejected from his apartment for not paying the rent.

senses.sense: (transitive) To throw out or remove forcefully.
examples: In other news, a Montreal man was ejected from his car when he was involved in an accident.

senses.sense: (US, transitive) To compel (a sports player) to leave the field because of inappropriate behaviour.
(usually intransitive) To forcefully project oneself or another occupant from an aircraft (or, rarely, another type of vehicle), typically using an ejection seat or escape capsule.
examples: The pilot lost control of the plane and had to eject.
As the crippled jet spiralled down, the pilot pulled the escape handle, ejecting first his rear-seater, then himself.

senses.sense: (transitive) To cause (something) to come out of a machine.
examples: Press that button to eject the video tape.

senses.sense: (intransitive) To come out of a machine.
examples: I can't get this cassette to eject.

senses.sense: (psychology, countable) an inferred object of someone else's consciousness
(geology) Material which has been ejected, especially from a volcano or an impact crater.
Able to be ejected.
(aerospace) Any object that is ejected by a satellite while it is in space.
